Important: This documentation is not in anyway finished!


@{b}Even more important:@{ub}


This is just a little note to say that MoneyManager will not be developed
any further for the Amiga if I don't get enough comments about how to improve
it or just comments to say that you find MoneyManager good/bad/awful/great
or whatever. (A Windows version will probably be made.)

There are several reasons for this especially the following:


@{b}1.@{ub}

MoneyManager pretty much fulfill my needs for a simple accounting program as
it is at the moment.


@{b}2.@{ub}

I haven't had many comments about MoneyManager although it was the 10th most
downloaded program on Aminet for a week or two when the first version was uploaded.


@{b}3.@{ub}

At the moment I'm beginning to consider the Amiga as being a dead platform mainly
because Amiga International doesn't come up with anything new neither software nor hardware.
And their choice of new hardware, the "SuperChip" doesn't seem like a very good way to me.
They should have started using standard mainstream components for the Amiga. Not doing this
will make the Amiga far too expensive compared to the PC and because of that it will probably
only be Amiga loving people who want to buy such a machine. Just look at the price of a towered
A1200 today, about 1000 pounds, this is far too much for an underpowered machine like that. In Denmark
you can get one of the fastest PC's for about 500-600 pounds without a monitor.


@{b}4.@{ub}

Just recently major former Amiga developing sofware companies where asked if they would
like to make games and applications for a new Amiga. Only about 20% answered yes to this question!

This seems like it's not very likely that Amiga International will be able to persuade those
software houses to restart their Amiga development.


@{b}Source:@{ub} Viva Text (Amiga Plus)


@{b}5.@{ub}

The last reason is that I, as a lot of other Amiga devoted people, am going to
buy a PC in the near future. (I have probably already bought it when you read this.)

I will off course keep my Amiga and hope that something good will happen. But I just
don't believe that anymore :-(


@{b}Last note:@{ub} If enough of you send me your opinions about MoneyManager I will keep
developing and improve it. And I'm willing to add your suggestions if I'm able to
do it. But still I need to hear from you for this to happen.

@endnode

@node "introduction" "MoneyManager: Introduction"
@smartwrap
MoneyManager is an very easy to use accounting program and it includes most of
the functions that you will need.


MoneyManager was made because most other accounting programs are crippled
shareware with a very limited number of possible transactions and in my
opinion there is no reason to pay about 25DM/15$ for a program like this.


MoneyManager was programmed in Oberon-A ©1995 by Frank Copeland and it uses
the Triton gui system ©1994-1995 by Stefan Zeiger.
@endnode

@node "requirements" "MoneyManager: Requirements"
@smartwrap
MoneyManager 1.1 Beta 1 requires OS3.0+ and triton.library installed in the LIBS:
directory.

In addition MoneyManager requires a stack size of at least 10000 bytes or
maybe even bigger if you have a lot of transactions (This is because of the
recursive nature of the QuickSort algoritm).
@endnode

