@node "menunew" "MoneyManager: New"
@smartwrap
Creates a new MoneyManager project.
@endnode

@node "menuopen" "MoneyManager: Open"
@smartwrap
Opens a filerequester for you to select a MoneyManager project file.
@endnode

@node "menusave" "MoneyManager: Save"
@smartwrap
Saves the MoneyManager project to the current file.
@endnode

@node "menusaveas" "MoneyManager: Save As"
@smartwrap
Opens a filerequester for you to choose a savefile for your MoneyManager
project.
@endnode

@node "menuabout" "MoneyManager: About"
@smartwrap
The traditional about requester.
@endnode

@node "menuquit" "MoneyManager: Quit"
@smartwrap
Just guess.
@endnode

@node "menugraph" "MoneyManager: Graph"
@smartwrap
Gives you a requester with a stringgadget. In this stringadget write the year
you want an income/outcome graph for and press the 'Ok' button. If you want a
graph of only one tag then press the 'Tag Graph' button and you will get a
requester where you can select a tag item to graph. (Please look at the @{"Bugs" link "bugs" 0}
section.)
@endnode

@node "menudeletealltags" "MoneyManager: Delete All Tags"
@smartwrap
Deletes all the defined tags. This is not done automatically when you choose
the 'New' menu item because you would probably use the same tags for all
projects.
@endnode

@node "menusettings" "MoneyManager: Settings"
@smartwrap
When chosen this menu item opens a settings window where you can specify if
you want encryption of your files or not. (Please look at the @{"Bugs" link "bugs" 0} section.)

@endnode

@node "menushowtag" "MoneyManager: Show Tag"
@smartwrap
Opens a requester where you can select a tag item to show.
@endnode

@node "menusavegnuplotdata" "MoneyManager: Save GNUPlot Data"
@smartwrap
When chosen this menu item opens a window where you can select the tag you
want to be saved in the GNUPlot datafile. When 'OK' has been pressed a filerequester
appears asking you to choose a file for saving the data.

The GNUPlot datafile will contain something like this:


#Money Manager GNUPlot Data


01/07/1998       6.00


28/08/1998      11.00


20/10/1998      12.00


21/10/1998      13.00


21/10/1998       4.00


23/10/1998      20.00


27/10/1998      13.00


27/10/1998      10.50


28/10/1998      20.00


28/10/1998       4.50


30/10/1998      14.75


03/11/1998      18.50


04/11/1998      13.00


06/11/1998      13.00




This data can be plotted with GNUPlot if you follow the instructions below:


Start up GNUPlot.


Type:


set xdata time


set timefmt "%d/%m/%Y"


set xrange ["01/07/1998":"10/05/1999"] (or whatever date range you want)


plot "<filename>" using 1:2 lines (or another mode of your own choice)




Please consult the GNUPlot manual for further instructions.

@endnode

